> while starting eclipse I20061212-0010 I got the following error in the error
> log...sorry no steps to reproduce.

Does it only occur on eclipse I20061212-0010? How about on 3.2, 3.2.1?

> java.lang.ClassCastException: gnu.javax.crypto.jce.DiffieHellmanImpl cannot be
> cast to javax.crypto.KeyAgreementSpi
> at javax.crypto.KeyAgreement.getInstance(KeyAgreement.java:129)
> at com.jcraft.jsch.jce.DH.init(Unknown Source)

It seems the problem has occured in JCE library.

> ....
> kernel version: Linux dual 2.6.18-1.2849.fc6 #1 SMP Fri Nov 10 12:36:14 EST
> 2006 i686 athlon i386 GNU/Linux
> gtk version: gtk2-2.10.4-6.fc6
> jre: sun 1.5.0_10

Is it true?
Run the following code on your environment,

  import java.security.NoSuchAlgorithmException;
  import javax.crypto.KeyAgreement;

  class foo {
      public static void main(String[] arg) {
          try {
              KeyAgreement myKeyAgree = KeyAgreement.getInstance("DH");
              System.out.println(myKeyAgree.getProvider());
          } catch (NoSuchAlgorithmException e) {
              // TODO Auto-generated catch block
              e.printStackTrace();
          }
      }
  }

If you are really running on Sun's JVM, you will have the following line,

  SunJCE version 1.5

I guess you are using gcj, which uses gnu-crypto as JCE provider,
because 'gnu.javax.crypto.jce.DiffieHellmanImpl' is referred. 

Of course, even if gcj is used, such an exception should not been thrown.

On Fedora Core 5, I can run above program and get following line successfully,

  gnu.java.security.provider.Gnu: name=GNU version=1.0

IMHO, there may be a problem in gcj installation on your environment.
